---
import "../styles/global.css";
import "../styles/index.css";
import Animation from "../components/Animation_lesson5.tsx";
import ProgressBar from "./progressbar.astro";
---

<html>
  <head>
    <link
      rel="icon"
      type="image/png"
      href="/DiET_teaching_blog_hdfs//favicon-h.png"
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <ProgressBar step={4} total={4} />
    <h1 style="text-align: center;">HDFS visualization</h1>

    <p class="py-8 max-w-[1000px] mx-auto">
      You have now learned how HDFS works: how files are divided into blocks, how those blocks are stored on DataNodes, and how the system manages storage across the data centre. <br>

      Below is the full visualization, where you can freely experiment with the system. You can choose how many files to store, select the DataNode the client connects to, and observe how storage is used and where blocks are placed. <br>

      A new feature in this view is the "Block mapping" inside the NameNode, which shows where all replicas of each block are stored for every file. <br>

      Try different configurations and explore how the system behaves under different scenarios.
    </p>

    <Animation client:load />

    <!-- References to previous and next page -->
    <div class="flex justify-center gap-4 mt-6">
      <a
        href=".."
        class="px-4 py-2 text-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)] rounded-lg hover:bg-[oklch(0.6831_0.1558_356.93)] border-2 border-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)]"
      >
        Back Home
      </a>

      <a
        href="../lesson4/"
        class="px-4 py-2 text-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)] rounded-lg hover:bg-[oklch(0.6831_0.1558_356.93)] border-2 border-[oklch(0.3816_0.1558_356.93)]"
      >
        Previous
      </a>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
